timeline_text: Design of a new library was completed by Proudfoot and Bird for a three-story, 51,853 square foot building. The Board approved these architectural plans in September, and in October 1922, work began to prepare the site for construction with the removal of trees followed by excavation. Foundation was poured in spring 1923, and the installation of ironwork for the stuperstructure began.
WOI library programming began
Library is moved to Central Building (Beardsheer Hall).
The College hosted a formal dedication ceremony in State Gymnasium for the new library.

Fanny Thomas is appointed as Librarian.  In fall 1891, a 1-hour course in Library Work is first taught. Though the content and course number have changed over the years, undergraudates are still required to take a library course.
The first floor of the new Library opened.
Iowa Agricultural College and Model Farm is established on March 22, 1858. The Library is housed in the Main Building until 1891.
Joseph Arthur is appointed as the first Librarian.
Dedication of Morrill Hall, which includes a new space for a library.
The Board approves $400,000 for a new library building.
An informal ceremony is held for the dedication of the new building cornerstone.
Charles Harvey Brown is hired as Dean of the Library.
WOI and the Library launched expanded programming, which eventually evolved into what is believed to be the first Radio Book Club in the nation

Artist Grant Wood served as head of the Public Works of Art Project for Iowa, and President Hughes asked him to plan murals for the library. They depict agricultural practices over time and major areas of study at Iowa State at the time of mural creation.
Library Storage Building opened; that structure is now the Advanced Machinery Systems Lab.
WWII brought many changes to campus, including services to state and national defense agencies, and a branch facility at Camp Dodge opened briefly.
Sculptor and Iowa State artist-in-residence Christian Petersen completed “Library Boy and Girl” sculptures, featured in the Library’s rotunda in the original building.
Robert Orr was named the new Director of the Library.

The Library’s need for more space became more dire as collections, college enrollment, and library staff continued to grow after WWII. Director Orr advocated for library expansions for many years before funding for an addition came to fruition.

Dorothy Kehlenbeck to collect and organize materials as Iowa State College approached its 100th anniversary, and she continued on as the Curator of the College Historical Collection, which eventually grew to be the start of University Archives.
Construction began on the Library’s first addition.

The Library’s first addition, designed by Brooks-Borg Architects, was completed. It included stacks and reader space, new stairs, an elevator, and restrooms added to the west side of the building and a new rotunda entrance on the south side.
The first addition didn’t alleviate space needs for long. By July 1967, ground broke for another addition.
Warren Kuhn was hired as the Director of the Library (1967-1971), and he was promoted to the position of Dean of Library Sciences in 1971.
Second expansion complete, located to the west and north of first addition
The Library reaches 1,000,000 volumes; Trattato della Pittura, by Lionardo da Vinci is the one-millionth volume.

timeline_title: Board of Regents Approves Third Addition Project
timeline_text: The Library again needs an addition to accommodate collections storage, increased seating, new and expanded services and departments, and changing technology needs. The ISU Foundation created a fund and capital campaign for this third addition, and the Board of Regents and the state legislature approved of this project in 1979.
Work began on the third addition in November 1980.
Third addition is complete. It was designed by Charles Herbert and Associates (which later became Herbert, Lewis, Kruse, Blunck).
Library was named for the University’s 11th president William Robert Parks and his wife, Ellen Sorge Parks.
